00:05:26.220 --> 00:05:30.880
If it's a slider, ask if it's
actually doing what you want it to.

00:05:30.880 --> 00:05:33.750
Can this information be conveyed
in a more user-friendly way

00:05:33.750 --> 00:05:36.610
that's more engaging
without having to also add

00:05:36.610 --> 00:05:39.280
all that extra required
interaction to it?

00:05:40.320 --> 00:05:44.910
In my case, the answer was,
Yes, proceed with the animation.

00:05:44.910 --> 00:05:48.570
So once we've answered the
should I question, that's

00:05:48.570 --> 00:05:52.022
when you start to
explore the requirements

00:05:52.023 --> 00:05:54.110
that you have to satisfy,

00:05:54.110 --> 00:05:56.010
and the reasons behind
those requirements.

00:05:56.010 --> 00:06:00.400
What are the issues that people
could have with motion and animation,

00:06:00.400 --> 00:06:03.500
and what can we do to
help them use our site?

00:06:03.500 --> 00:06:06.930
As it says on the slide here,
animations can present a variety

00:06:06.930 --> 00:06:09.610
of barriers or issues
for website visitors.

00:06:09.610 --> 00:06:12.600
We want to provide a way that
respects their initial settings

00:06:12.600 --> 00:06:15.260
and then lets them decide
how they want to proceed.

00:06:15.260 --> 00:06:18.720
So this is our mission
statement for our animation.

00:06:18.720 --> 00:06:21.290
We'd be respecting the
reduced-motion options

00:06:21.290 --> 00:06:24.820
and then giving them the option
to then completely stop animations

00:06:24.820 --> 00:06:26.420
and movement altogether.

00:06:26.420 --> 00:06:29.520
This falls under four success
criterion outlined here,

00:06:29.520 --> 00:06:32.250
depending on the type of
animation that you're adding.

00:06:32.250 --> 00:06:35.870
You have 2.2.2,
which is pause, stop, hide.

00:06:35.870 --> 00:06:38.180
That's A level requirement.

00:06:38.180 --> 00:06:42.340
It's about information that's on the
page for longer than five seconds,

00:06:42.340 --> 00:06:46.560
so that when it gets paused,
any sliders won't auto play.

00:06:46.560 --> 00:06:50.550
You can implement a more
subtle transition than a slide,

00:06:50.550 --> 00:06:52.260
like a fade, for instance.

00:06:52.260 --> 00:06:57.330
Switch out those fancy new marquees
that have been popping up now

00:06:57.330 --> 00:06:59.450
as the latest trend.

00:06:59.450 --> 00:07:02.530
Create a non-moving
text banner instead.

00:07:02.530 --> 00:07:05.890
Pause the circle that's
going around constantly.

00:07:05.890 --> 00:07:08.590
This is for people who
can't read quickly.

00:07:08.590 --> 00:07:12.170
For automatically moving text,
which can provide problems

00:07:12.170 --> 00:07:17.200
for screen readers, it provides
severe distraction, which interferes

00:07:17.200 --> 00:07:20.430
with the ability to concentrate
on other parts of the page.

00:07:20.430 --> 00:07:23.521
It can cause nausea,
dizziness, headaches

00:07:23.522 --> 00:07:25.950
if scrolling page elements move.

00:07:25.950 --> 00:07:28.970
It can trigger the vestibular
or inner ear disorders.

00:07:28.970 --> 00:07:32.760
Flashing or blinking can cause
seizures due to photosensitivity.

00:07:32.760 --> 00:07:34.990
There's a lot of things here that
people could have problems with

00:07:34.990 --> 00:07:37.800
when it comes to
motion and animation.

00:07:37.800 --> 00:07:39.230
There's also three other ones.

00:07:39.230 --> 00:07:41.370
There's 2.3.1.

00:07:41.370 --> 00:07:45.520
Three flashes are below
threshold, and that's A level.

00:07:45.520 --> 00:07:48.600
Then there's the AAA level,
which is just three flashes.

00:07:48.600 --> 00:07:50.750
That's 2.3.2.

00:07:50.750 --> 00:07:57.140
Then you have the .31, which is
the animation from interaction,

00:07:57.140 --> 00:07:58.700
which is also AAA.

00:07:59.730 --> 00:08:03.260
So just as a quick differentiation,
pause, stop, hide is

00:08:03.260 --> 00:08:07.280
when the page loads and
initiates the animation.

00:08:07.280 --> 00:08:10.480
So content loading, page
loading, anything like that.

00:08:10.480 --> 00:08:13.680
Animation from interaction is the
user initiating the interaction

00:08:13.680 --> 00:08:15.350
like hover or scrolling.

00:08:15.350 --> 00:08:19.820
And how you handle the A level
is pretty much how you handle

00:08:19.820 --> 00:08:23.540
and address the AAA level,
which is all for a way to pause

00:08:23.540 --> 00:08:25.460
and respect user preferences.

00:08:27.090 --> 00:08:30.510
Some of our options to
address these would be

00:08:30.510 --> 00:08:34.030
to just remove page
load, scroll features,

00:08:34.030 --> 00:08:37.190
stick a pause button
under each animation.

00:08:37.190 --> 00:08:40.900
But we want to make
this as easy as possible

00:08:40.900 --> 00:08:43.840
while still giving a fun
experience, right?

00:08:43.840 --> 00:08:46.880
We don't want them to have to
pause every single animation

00:08:46.880 --> 00:08:50.600
by having a toggle button
at the top of the page.

00:08:50.600 --> 00:08:53.090
We give someone the ability
to control that animation

00:08:53.090 --> 00:08:56.930
before they get there, rather
than having to be exposed to it

00:08:56.930 --> 00:08:57.930
and then pause it.

00:08:59.830 --> 00:09:02.840
There’s a media query that
I'll refer to as we go,

00:09:02.840 --> 00:09:05.460
prefers-reduced-motion,
that we're going look at.

00:09:05.460 --> 00:09:07.360
But that means reduced
motion, right?

00:09:07.360 --> 00:09:10.050
You don't have to just
remove all animation totally.

00:09:11.610 --> 00:09:15.090
You provide a pared-down
experience in terms of movement.

00:09:15.090 --> 00:09:19.350
So we can use that and respect
it, and then give people a way

00:09:19.350 --> 00:09:23.130
to control the animation that
maybe don't want to set it

00:09:23.130 --> 00:09:24.450
on their computers.

00:09:24.450 --> 00:09:26.670
Maybe they want to
temporarily pause it.

00:09:26.670 --> 00:09:28.510
So we're offering options here.

00:09:28.510 --> 00:09:30.450
I also kind of like the
idea of giving someone

00:09:30.450 --> 00:09:35.900
who turned on reduced motion to
allow the website to show the motion

00:09:35.900 --> 00:09:36.700
if they wanted.

00:09:36.700 --> 00:09:39.630
I sometimes turn it on and
off based on my own needs

00:09:39.630 --> 00:09:44.610
regarding overstimulation, eye
strain, depending on what the type

00:09:44.610 --> 00:09:46.800
of animation is,
it'll make me a little bit dizzy.

00:09:48.430 --> 00:09:50.860
How great would it be if
I had an option on a site

00:09:50.860 --> 00:09:53.600
that let me decide what I
wanted to do in that moment?

00:09:53.600 --> 00:09:57.330
I think this is kind of where
those accessibility overlays,

00:09:57.330 --> 00:10:01.280
their intention hopefully came
from, which is to allow users

00:10:01.280 --> 00:10:03.980
to control things on a site
without having to set it

00:10:03.980 --> 00:10:07.130
on their computer settings,
but they haven't done it in a way

00:10:07.130 --> 00:10:11.240
that's accessible, and they create
more problems than they solve.

00:10:11.240 --> 00:10:14.250
So what we're doing is targeting
a very specific situation

00:10:14.250 --> 00:10:17.740
that directly applies to our
website, and ensuring that it works

00:10:17.740 --> 00:10:18.870
for our site.

00:10:18.870 --> 00:10:20.908
We're not providing
100 different options

00:10:20.909 --> 00:10:22.510
that somebody has to go through.

00:10:22.510 --> 00:10:23.960
We're providing this
one thing that's going

00:10:23.960 --> 00:10:26.550
to enhance the user's experience.

00:10:26.550 --> 00:10:29.240
A big part of this is
making the right decisions.

00:10:29.240 --> 00:10:31.810
If an animation is going to blink,
it's going to be distracting,

00:10:31.810 --> 00:10:34.090
if it's going to be
a problem for someone

00:10:34.090 --> 00:10:37.770
before they can even find the
pause button, don't do it.

00:10:37.770 --> 00:10:40.770
Just because you can add a button to
a site doesn't give you permission

00:10:40.770 --> 00:10:42.530
to now do whatever you want.

00:10:42.530 --> 00:10:45.790
We're just thinking of a
better user experience here.

00:10:45.790 --> 00:10:48.210
So with that, here's what
we're going to be building.

00:10:49.550 --> 00:10:55.450
It's a button that controls an
animation play or pause state.

00:10:55.450 --> 00:11:00.210
It should default to the user's
preferences and save the state

00:11:00.210 --> 00:11:02.080
of the button across pages.

00:11:02.080 --> 00:11:05.290
It should be accessible to
people using a mouse, a keyboard,

00:11:05.290 --> 00:11:06.200
or a screen reader.

00:11:06.200 --> 00:11:09.160
So that's our project summary here.

