me, tell me about it,

00:48:04.100 --> 00:48:08.500
and I can sort of be a little more
informed about how to approach it.

00:48:08.500 --> 00:48:09.920
I don't really know much about it.

00:48:09.920 --> 00:48:11.970
Is it an animation library?

00:48:11.970 --> 00:48:12.970
Is that what it is?

00:48:14.580 --> 00:48:15.580
RONAK: OK.

00:48:16.540 --> 00:48:17.820
Thank you, Danielle.

00:48:19.180 --> 00:48:19.680
DANIELLE: Yes.

00:48:19.680 --> 00:48:21.450
So if that's what it
is, I don't know.

00:48:22.620 --> 00:48:24.810
My first instinct would be
to answer is it’s probably

00:48:24.810 --> 00:48:27.190
as accessible as somebody makes it.

00:48:27.190 --> 00:48:30.950
So if it's an animation library,
it's going to be something

00:48:30.950 --> 00:48:33.500
that somebody's going
to use and put together.

00:48:33.500 --> 00:48:33.800
Let's see.

00:48:33.800 --> 00:48:36.840
Threejs allows you to use
3d models and web design

00:48:36.840 --> 00:48:42.220
and then the motion sensitivity.
Again, my first instinct is

00:48:42.220 --> 00:48:48.310
to say have it be a conditional
thing, like, only showing on people

00:48:48.310 --> 00:48:52.650
who explicitly allow it,
and then user test it.

00:48:52.650 --> 00:48:55.600
I would say it probably depends
on how much motion you're adding,

00:48:55.600 --> 00:48:59.000
how much blinking there is.

00:48:59.000 --> 00:49:03.590
It's going to really depend on what
you're doing within that 3D element.

00:49:03.590 --> 00:49:05.600
And then I would say that kind
of stuff, you probably have

00:49:05.600 --> 00:49:08.860
to user test and get some feedback
on whether it causes issues

00:49:08.860 --> 00:49:09.860
for people.

